      "name": "Hemolysis index validation — steady-state FDA pump (comparator link absent)",
      "description": "CFD-predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) values at five steady-state operating points (3 L/min–6000 RPM, 5 L/min–5000 RPM, 7 L/min–4500 RPM, 4 L/min–5500 RPM, 6 L/min–4000 RPM) are compared against benchtop plasma-free hemoglobin measurements reported by Fraser et al. (2011) for the FDA generic centrifugal pump. Mean absolute error across the five points is 0.0031 mg/dL·min. The comparator dataset is described in the narrative as 'Fraser-2011-steady-state-PIV' but the formal comparedAgainst link is omitted from this record. NOTE: The COU requires pulsatile flow validation (time-varying inlet waveform, heart-rate 70 bpm, stroke volume 70 mL); the Fraser 2011 dataset uses fixed-RPM, non-pulsatile conditions. This regime mismatch means the comparator is inappropriate for the declared COU even though numerical agreement appears favorable at steady state. The absence of the comparedAgainst triple prevents automated detection of this mismatch.",
      "validationMetric": "Mean absolute error in NIH: 0.0031 mg/dL·min",
      "validationStatus": "pass-steady-state-only"
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/comparator-mismatch-explicit",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Hemolysis index validation — pulsatile conditions (comparator present but regime mismatch flagged)",
      "description": "A secondary validation attempt used the Hariharan et al. (2011) FDA pump dataset, also collected under steady-state conditions, as a surrogate for pulsatile VAD operation. The comparedAgainst link is populated below. However, neither the Fraser nor the Hariharan dataset includes pulsatile inlet waveforms; both were acquired at constant rotational speed and constant volumetric flow rate. The COU explicitly requires pulsatile operation (sinusoidal inlet waveform at 1.17 Hz). The use of steady-state experimental comparators to validate a pulsatile-flow model constitutes an inference-method mismatch: agreement under steady-state conditions does not bound hemolysis prediction error under pulsatile shear-stress histories. This mismatch is noted here but was not treated as a disqualifying gap in the decision record.",
